snippet.textDisplay:
This is the first Wes Anderson movie I have no interest in seeing (besides The Darjeeling Limited, which I turned off early because of the insulting guy having sex with “exotic” brown woman on the train scene - you know the one to satisfy the white guy can go around the world and have sex with any of the indigenous women myth).

He’s bringing nothing new to the table at this point. Other pop culture Directors (or Directors in general) grow up - Spielberg, Scorsese, etc... Wes just keeps putting the same movie out with a different spin combined with the “it” actors at the time (now it’s Timothy Chalamet) and quirky obscure imagery and costumes, then calls it artistic.

It was interesting at one point, but after 20 years it’s getting old.

snippet.textDisplay:
The International Medical Travel Journal (IMTJ) reported on May 13 and June 7 that Belgium's primary legislative body had passed a new bill on April 25 that would punish all parties involved in the buying and selling of human organs for commercial purposes, citing a recent report from The Epoch Times.

A clause in the bill references a resolution condemning forced organ harvesting in China, which was passed by the European Parliament in December 2013.


Belgium legislative body building

Violators face up to 20 years of imprisonment with a €1.2m (USD$1.35 million) fine. If an organized criminal group is involved in such trade, all individuals in the group will face punishment.
